info.title: Navirec API
info.description:
# Introduction

The Navirec API is a RESTful web service for developers to programmatically interact with Navirec data.

The Navirec API is organized around REST. Every bit of data exchanged between clients and the API is JSON over HTTPS. 
All API requests must be made over HTTPS. Calls made over plain HTTP will fail. You must authenticate for all requests.

The base URL for the Navirec API is https://api.navirec.com/.

If you have questions about using the API, or have come across a bug you'd like to report, write us an email at <api@navirec.com>.

## User-Agent

Set a clearly identifiable User-Agent HTTP header that is unique to your company & integration software being used.
This makes our admin staff fully aware of your integration and allows us to keep your solution fully operational.

Please use only printable ASCII characters.

Examples that we consider a good practice. Please substitute your own names in the examples. 

```http request
User-Agent: MyDomain.com
User-Agent: MyApplication
User-Agent: MyApplication/1.0.0
User-Agent: MyApplication/1.0.0 (python-requests/2.24.0)
```

## Versioning

All API requests should specify the version of the API that the integration was built with.
This version number needs to be appended to the Accept HTTP header as an additional argument.

In the following example, replace `X.Y.Z` with the most recent version number given at the top of the documentation page.

```http request
GET /trips/ HTTP/1.1
Host: api.navirec.com
Accept: application/json; version=X.Y.Z
User-Agent: MyApplication/1.0.0
```

It is possible to use the browsable API without specifying the version, but this is intended
for developer convenience only. All requests made by production systems need to include the 
version in the Accept header. 

## Language

The API will respond with names and labels in English by default. If you wish to receive localized responses,
then you can indicate the preferred language using the following HTTP header:

```http request
Accept-Language: et
```

The response headers will also indicate the content language as a confirmation.

```http request
Content-Language: et
```

## Time zones

The timestamps in the API are represented in the ISO-8601 format including the time zone indicator (Z)
which means these timestamps are in UTC by default. The timestamps shown in the web and mobile apps are in the
account timezone, which is usually not UTC.

If you wish to communicate with the API without converting between local and UTC timestamps, then you can indicate
the timezone you wish to use from the valid IANA timezone identifier list by providing the following HTTP Header:

```http request
Accept-Timezone: Europe/Tallinn
```

The API will respond with the timestamps converted to that timezone including the correct UTC offset indicator.
The response headers will also indicate the content timezone as a confirmation.

```http request
Content-Timezone: Europe/Tallinn
```

## Pagination

Navirec API uses Link Header Pagination for most endpoints (except Last Vehicle States and Last Driver States).

For example when requesting a list of vehicles and the number of objects exceeds 100, then the API will respond with
the first 100 objects and a link to fetch the next 100 objects. The link is stored in the `Link` header with attribute `rel="next"`.
The provided link will have the same query arguments as your original query but with the `cursor` attribute updated.

```http request
GET /vehicles/?ordering=id

HTTP 200 OK
Allow: GET, HEAD, OPTIONS
Content-Type: application/json
Link: <https://api.navirec.com/vehicles/?cursor=cD0wMDQ3N2M4My1jOTYzLTQzYjAtOTM4MC0xNDY1ODY1ZjYwZTg%3D&ordering=id>; rel="next"
Vary: Accept
```

Then you can use that link to fetch the next 100 objects. That response will also include a link to the previous page
with attribute `rel="prev"`.

```http request
GET /vehicles/?cursor=cD0wMDQ3N2M4My1jOTYzLTQzYjAtOTM4MC0xNDY1ODY1ZjYwZTg%3D&ordering=id

HTTP 200 OK
Allow: GET, HEAD, OPTIONS
Content-Type: application/json
Link: 
 <https://api.navirec.com/vehicles/?cursor=cD0wMDhlN2Q0Mi04Mjk5LTQ1YjMtYjc0Ny1hMjZkMjA2YjRiNmE%3D&ordering=id>; rel="next", 
 <https://api.navirec.com/vehicles/?cursor=cj0xJnA9MDA0N2QwNTYtMWFlZS00MDVhLTk4MjctNGI2NWNhNmZjZWY1&ordering=id>; rel="prev"
Vary: Accept
```

When setting a custom `ordering` parameter value in your queries, then we advise to always include a unique
field in your `ordering` parameter to guarantee persistent ordering across queries to different pages. For example
when sorting first by `name`, then append `id` to have the final query argument set to `ordering=name,id`.

Response page size can be customized using the `page_size` query attribute (up to 1000 objects per request).

An excellent documentation describing how link header pagination works has been made available by GitHub on
https://docs.github.com/en/rest/guides/traversing-with-pagination

## Rate limits

Navirec API is rate limited to ensure fair access to available resources. Clients are expected to handle responses 
with status HTTP 429 Too Many Requests appropriately by waiting the number of seconds indicated by the `Retry-After`
response header. In the next example, the API client is expected to wait a minimum of 3 seconds before attempting 
the request again.

```http request
GET /drivers/

HTTP 429 Too Many Requests
Allow: GET, POST, HEAD, OPTIONS
Content-Type: application/json
Retry-After: 3
Vary: Accept

{
    "detail": "Request was throttled. Expected available in 3 seconds."
}
```

An overview of the current limits is provided purely for informative reasons. 
These limits are subject to change without prior notice when necessary to maintain operation.

Session-based limits:

* anonymous: 100/hour
* authenticated sessions: 120/minute, 1800/hour
  
In addition to session-based limits, some endpoints are limited further:

* authenticate: 10/hour
* areas: 24/minute, 400/hour
* trips: 24/minute, 200/hour
* notifications: 24/minute, 200/hour
* vehicle_timeline: 24/minute, 100/hour
* driver_timeline: 24/minute, 100/hour
* vehicle_history: 24/minute, 100/hour
* last_vehicle_states: 24/minute
* last_driver_states: 24/minute
* stream_vehicle_states: 6/minute
* stream_driver_states: 6/minute

## Errors

Navirec uses conventional HTTP response codes to indicate success or failure of an API request. In general, codes in the 2xx range indicate success, codes in the 4xx range indicate an error that resulted from the provided information (e.g. a required parameter was missing, a charge failed, etc.), and codes in the 5xx range indicate an error with Navirec's servers.

| Status code | Status text       | Description                                |
|-------------|-------------------|--------------------------------------------|
| 200         | OK                | Everything                                 |
| 400         | Bad Request       | Often missing a required parameter.        |
| 401         | Unauthorized      | No valid API key provided.                 |
| 402         | Request Failed    | Parameters were valid but request failed.  |
| 404         | Not Found         | The requested item doesn't exist.          |
| 429         | Too Many Requests | Too many requests hit the API too quickly. |
| 50*         | Server Errors     | Something went wrong on our end.           |

## Sideloading

Some list endpoints support sideloading of the related objects. It can be used by providing `sideload` query param. 
Note that this will change response type from List to object and items will have nested lists of requested objects. 

Example request: 

    /emails/?sideload=accounts,drivers,contacts 


Body:

```json    
    {
       "email":[
          ...
       ],
       "accounts":[
          ...
       ],
       "drivers":[
          ...
       ],
       "contacts":[
          ...
       ]
    }
```

## Data streaming

Live GPS tracking data streams of vehicle and driver states is provided with two streaming endpoints:

* `/streams/driver_states/` - returns current driver states and then all subsequent updates
* `/streams/vehicle_states/` - returns current vehicle states and then all subsequent updates

The data format in the streams is compatible with previously available polling endpoints
[last driver states](#tag/Last-driver-states) and [last vehicle states](#tag/Last-vehicle-states).
However, instead of a single JSON list object containing all the state objects, the streaming endpoints 
return state objects in the Newline Delimited JSON (ndjson) Format. 

Query arguments for `/streams/driver_states/`:
 
* `account`
* `driver`
* `driver_group`
* `active`
* `updated_at__gt`

Query arguments for `/streams/vehicle_states/`:

* `account`
* `primary_account`
* `vehicle`
* `vehicles`
* `vehicle_groups`
* `active`
* `updated_at__gt`

Each event in the stream may contain the following fields:

* `id`: a globally unique identifier for the data in the event (optional, only for vehicle_state, driver_state)
* `event`: type of event received (connected, vehicle_state, driver_state, initial_state_sent, heartbeat, disconnected)
* `data`: a json object with data (optional, only for vehicle_state, driver_state)

Event types:

* `connected`: sent at the moment the stream is initialized
* `vehicle_state`: GPS tracking info from a vehicle (only from `/streams/vehicle_states/`)
* `driver_state`: driver state info based on driver recognition tools (only from `/streams/driver_states/`)
* `initial_state_sent`: indicates that the API has sent all currently known state data and will continue to send new state data once it becomes available
* `heartbeat`: sent every 30 seconds to prevent idle connections from timing out
* `disconnected`: sent before recycling the connection in about 1h. the client is expected to reconnect.

Example request:

```http request
GET https://api.navirec.com/streams/vehicle_states/?account=<account_id>

User-Agent: IntegrationApp123
Accept: application/x-ndjson; version=1.33.0
Accept-Timezone: Europe/Tallinn
Authorization: Token eyJ0e..redacted..9ch0A
```

The streams are kept open from the API side until either the client terminates the request or the server process
restarts (e.g. during a software update or container restart). In this case, the client may reconnect to the stream
and provide the last known `updated_at` timestamp to re-initialize the stream at that position.

Then the next API call should be like this:

```http request
GET https://api.navirec.com/streams/vehicle_states/?account=<account_id>&updated_at__gt=2024-02-16T14:02:41.127646Z
```

# Authentication

Please use the Navirec web application to generate an API token.
The API token management page is located in Profile menu -> Account settings -> 
[API access](https://app.navirec.com/account/api-access/).

After creating the access token for a new integration, you must also assign permissions to the newly
created integration user. Click on the integration name in the table to edit permissions.

For clients to authenticate, the token key should be included in the Authorization HTTP header.
The key should be prefixed by the string literal "Token", with whitespace separating the two strings.

`Authorization: Token eyJhbGc.example.ssw5c`
    
Note: you must replace `eyJhbGc.example.ssw5c` with the newly created API token.
# Changelog

Version 1.45.0:

* Fixed minor OpenAPI schema inconsistencies
* Trip Report: added fields `resolution_positive_user_names`, `resolution_negative_user_names`, `resolution_missing_user_names`
* Trip Report: changed fields `vehicle_group_names` and `driver_group_names` from comma separated string to array of strings

Version 1.44.0:

* Vehicles: added field `hourly_co2_emission`
* Trips Report: added `split_by`, `layout`, `pivot_row_group_by`, `pivot_column_group_by`, `pivot_value_column` report parameters to `TripSummaryReportParamsSerializer`
* Vehicle Event Report: added `split_by`, `layout`, `pivot_row_group_by`, `pivot_column_group_by`, `pivot_value_column` report parameters to `VehicleEventReportParamsSerializer`
* Tanking Report: added `split_by`, `layout`, `pivot_row_group_by`, `pivot_column_group_by`, `pivot_value_column` report parameters to `TankingReportParamsSerializer`
* Sensors Report: added `layout` report parameter to `SensorReportParamsSerializer`
* ReportRecurrence: removed field `send_empty_reports`

Version 1.43.0:

* Area groups: added fields `name` & `group_type`
* Area groups: added "All areas" groups for every account (`group_type`: `default`)
* Fuel cards: added field `fuel_card_groups`
* Fuel card groups: the endpoint has been made available
* Reports (all types): added actions `preview` and `convert`
* Report links: the endpoint has been made available
* Sensors report: 
  * added fields `vehicles` & `vehicle_groups`
  * removed field `vehicle`
  * Introduce `vehicle_name` & `vehicle_registration` in data actions
* Tankings: replaced field `integration` with `source`
* Tanking report: added quick filter `fuel_card_groups`
* Trips: added fields `start_area` and `end_area`
* Webhooks: added field `created_by`

Version 1.42.0:

* Trips: enhanced bulk actions with new date range and account filtering
  * Added `account`, `start_date`, and `end_date` fields to `TripTypeSerializer`
  * Added `account`, `start_date`, and `end_date` fields to `TripConfirmationSerializer`
  * Added `account`, `start_date`, and `end_date` fields to `TripCommentSerializer`
  * Added `account`, `start_date`, and `end_date` fields to `TripDriverSerializer`
  * Added `account`, `start_date`, and `end_date` fields to `TripAdditionalFieldSerializer`
  * Added `account`, `start_date`, and `end_date` fields to `TripResolutionsSerializer`
  * Improved filtering capabilities for trip operations
* Vehicle Management: Enhanced fuel consumption tracking
  * Added `hourly_fuel_consumption` field to `VehicleSerializer`
* Report Scheduling: Modernized recurrence rule system
  * Added `recurrence_rule` field to `ReportRecurrenceSerializer` supporting RFC 5545 RRULE format
  * Added `next_execution_time` field to `ReportRecurrenceSerializer`
  * Enhanced timezone-aware scheduling with automatic conversion from legacy cron expressions
  * Improved validation and error handling for recurrence patterns
  * Renamed field `enabled` to `active` in `ReportRecurrenceSerializer`
  * Added `format_options` field to `ReportRecurrenceSerializer`
* Report Requests: Enhanced configuration options
  * Added `format_options` field to `ReportRequestSerializer`
* Pagination and Filtering: Improved data access
  * Added `cursor` field to `BaseReportParamsSerializer` for enhanced pagination
  * Added `page_size` parameter to report request params
* Report Types and Sections: Composite reporting capabilities
  * Introduced `composite` report type with new endpoint `/reports/composite/`
  * Added stream endpoint for reports
  * New endpoint for composite report sections at `/report_sections/`
* Export System: Enhanced file upload workflow
  * Added `file_upload` field to `ExportSerializer` for direct file upload support
  * Support for `POST`, `PUT`, `PATCH` and `DELETE` actions

Version 1.41.0:

* Trips: several field changes
  * added `start_total_engine_time`
  * renamed `total_engine_time` -> `end_total_engine_time`
  * renamed `fuel_at_start` -> `start_fuel_level`
  * renamed `fuel_at_end` -> `end_fuel_level`
  * renamed `odometer_start` -> `start_odometer`
  * renamed `odometer_end` -> `end_odometer`

Version 1.40.1:

* Webhook requests: changes in outgoing data
  * Renamed HTTP header `X-Navirec-Account-ID`to `Navirec-Account-ID`
  * Renamed HTTP header `X-Navirec-Webhook-ID`to `Navirec-Webhook-ID`
  * Added HTTP header `Navirec-API-Version`
  * Added HTTP header `Navirec-Hmac-SHA256`
  * Notification webhook payload structure has changed to include `vehicle` and `area`

Version 1.40.0:

* Accounts: added field `password_authentication_enabled`
* Authenticate: added required field `authentication_method`
* Configuration: changed to return status 400 instead of 401 when authentication requirements are not met
* Users: added fields `country` and `personal_number` to the create operation
* Tachograph files, tachograph requests: method `export` error response field `detail` is no longer an array, but a string

Version 1.39.2:

* Environment: added field `web_app_release_track`

Version 1.39.1:

* Users: for new regular users, the `username` should be a valid e-mail address
* Users: for new integration users, the `username` should start with `integration_`

Version 1.39.0:

* Configuration: added service `address_search`
* Password reset: added API endpoints `password_reset` and `password_reset_confirm`

Version 1.38.0:

* Vehicle Timeline: a new endpoint that returns totals with daily details for vehicles at endpoint `vehicle_timeline/totals/`
* Driver Timeline: a new endpoint that returns totals with daily details for drivers at endpoint `driver_timeline/totals/`

Version 1.37.0:

* Driver and vehicle timeline: added fields `chart_lines`, `timeline_event.chart_line_id` and `warnings`
* Sensors: added field `chart_axis_id`

Version 1.36.1:

* Tachograph cards: added fields `card_icc_identification` and `card_chip_identification`

Version 1.36.0:

* Accounts: added field `active_in_countries`
* Drivers: added support for `sideload` argument
* Vehicle states: added fields `trail`, `activity_distance` and `activity_engine_time`

Version 1.35.0:

* Vehicle history: renamed field `accumulated_distance` to `accumulated_driving_distance`
* Data layers: added fields `fill_color`, `line_color`, `line_width` & `opacity`
* Driver and vehicle timeline: changed default for field `include_geometry` to False

Version 1.34.4

* Vehicle & driver timeline: added query parameter `include_timing`
* Vehicle & driver timeline: added field `timing` to `events`

Version 1.34.3

get.description:
Fetch last known driver state info including detected vehicle, working time etc.

__This endpoint is rate limited and using it for polling state updates in new integrations is discouraged.__

__For efficient real-time streaming of state updates, please see the section on [data streaming](#section/Introduction/Data-streaming).__


Filtering is required for this resource. Apply one of the following query parameters:
account, driver, driver_group

Fetch info regarding all drivers in your account by calling:

`https://api.navirec.com/last_driver_states/?account=<account_id>`

In each response there is a HTTP Header `X-Updated-At-Max`, which should be used as a starting value for each next call 
into that same endpoint. This will ensure that you only get updated driver data and skip the data 
that you have already downloaded in the last request.

For example, when the response contains the following header:

`X-Updated-At-Max: 2018-08-24T08:30:50.793114Z`

Then the next API call should be like this:

`https://api.navirec.com/last_driver_states/?account=<account_id>&updated_at__gt=2018-08-24T08:30:50.793114Z`

parameters.name: account
parameters.description: Filter by account id.

parameters.name: active
parameters.description: Filter by active state.

parameters.name: driver
parameters.description: Filter by driver id.

parameters.name: driver_group
parameters.description: Filter by driver group id.

parameters.name: updated_at__gt
parameters.description: Filter by updated_at timestamp greater than.

`https://api.navirec.com/last_vehicle_states/?account=<account_id>`

In each response there is a HTTP Header `X-Updated-At-Max`, which should be used as a starting value for each next call

that you have already downloaded in the last request.

For example, when the response contains the following header:

`X-Updated-At-Max: 2018-08-24T08:30:50.793114Z`

Then the next API call should be like this:

`https://api.navirec.com/last_vehicle_states/?account=<account_id>&updated_at__gt=2018-08-24T08:30:50.793114Z`

post.operationId: Tachograph requests â†’ create
post.description:
Create a Tachograph Request with specified parameters.

Fields `period_start` and `period_end` specify the period for the data requested from the tachograph.
The provided values will be used for all non-recurring requests. However, when `recurring` is `true`, then
these values will be calculated automatically and any provided values will be overridden.

Field `recurring` indicates that the request should automatically repeat according to the rule specified in field
`recurrence_rule` using the 
[iCalendar Recurrence Rule format](https://icalendar.org/iCalendar-RFC-5545/3-8-5-3-recurrence-rule.html).

When `recurring` is `true`, then a valid rule must be provided in `recurrence_rule`. 

Constraints for `recurrence_rule`:
* Must include **DTSTART** with the account timezone. Example: `DTSTART:20200101T000000Z`.
* May include **UNTIL** with the last recurrence end datetime but it must be in UTC using the Zulu time zone abbreviation. Using the same time as **DTSTART** example: `UNTIL=20191231T220000Z`.
* The instance first created will be from **DTSTART** to first instance of the rule or **UNTIL** if none exist between **DTSTART** and **UNTIL**

get.description:
Fetch vehicle events: ignition and other digital input switches, 
trips and other activities starting and ending, area enters and exits and notifications that were triggered.

Filtering is required for this resource. Apply one of the following query parameters:
account, primary_account, vehicle, vehicle_group

Time-based filtering is highly recommended as it will reduce the responses considerably.
Arguments should be specified in ISO8601 compatible formatting. For example:                    

`https://api.navirec.com/last_vehicle_states/?account=<account_id>&time__gte=2019-08-04T21:00:00.000Z&time__lte=2019-08-05T20:59:59.000Z`

Limit events by type by applying the interpretation or interpretation__in filters, e.g.:            

`https://api.navirec.com/last_vehicle_states/?account=<account_id>&time__gte=2019-08-04T21:00:00.000Z&time__lte=2019-08-05T20:59:59.000Z&interpretation__in=driving,idling`
